{
  "answer": "The passage likening the cosmic veil of illusion (*māyā*) to a honeycomb crowded with souls appears in the *Vrhaspatitattva*, Chapter 1.[^1]\n\n> *Māyā* is like the honeycomb, and the *ātmā* is like the young bees. They are face-down, which means they are bent over; the *ātmā* looks only downward, unaware of the *tattva* above it.[^1]\n\nThe surrounding context matches your description precisely: *Śivatattva*, originally crystal-clear, becomes stained by *mala* (impurity) and so \"ceases to be all-knowing and all-doing,\" at which point it is renamed *ātmā*, meaning \"dazed consciousness,\" with the souls (*ātmatattvas*) multiplying until *māyātattva* is \"crowded, like a honeycomb, layered and stacked.\"[^1]\n\n[^1]: *Vrhaspatitattva*, [paragraph](/works/unknown-vrhaspatitattva-b60b28/01/translation/#p-643885).",
